00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:57,436
Oh, and one Inspector Harry Callahan.

238
00:24:58,938 --> 00:25:02,931
Johnny Squares is on that list.
See what's written by his name?

239
00:25:03,943 --> 00:25:07,538
Yeah, RIP. "Rest in peace."

240
00:25:10,150 --> 00:25:11,515
You know what this is?

241
00:25:11,718 --> 00:25:14,016
It's a bill for a TV camera and lens.

242
00:25:14,220 --> 00:25:18,281
When I said stop wrecking cars,
I didn't mean destroy something else.

243
00:25:18,491 --> 00:25:21,051
They interfered
with an investigation, sir.

244
00:25:21,261 --> 00:25:24,992
Don't give us that. Is this
your idea of media cooperation?

245
00:25:25,198 --> 00:25:27,393
Cooperation works two ways.

246
00:25:27,600 --> 00:25:30,091
What is it you have against reporters?

247
00:25:30,303 --> 00:25:32,737
Some of them
are just marvelous people.

248
00:25:32,939 --> 00:25:36,932
Others walk through a pile and track
it through an investigation.

249
00:25:37,143 --> 00:25:39,304
You better change
your attitude fast.

250
00:25:39,512 --> 00:25:42,447
Because unless we
reach an agreement with them...

251
00:25:42,649 --> 00:25:46,244
...it's liable to cost this city
2 million, and your career.

252
00:25:48,421 --> 00:25:49,752
Join us, please.

253
00:25:49,956 --> 00:25:52,618
This is Ms. Samantha Walker
of station IKKWSF.

254
00:25:52,826 --> 00:25:53,724
Captain Donnelly.

255
00:25:53,927 --> 00:25:57,158
- Ms. Walker.
- Captain.

256
00:25:57,364 --> 00:26:00,197
- And this is Inspector...
- Callahan. We've met.

257
00:26:00,400 --> 00:26:03,699
Yes, of course. Won't you sit down?

258
00:26:05,772 --> 00:26:06,761
Ms. Walker...

259
00:26:06,973 --> 00:26:11,069
...Lieutenant Ackerman tells me
you have a proposal to make...

260
00:26:11,277 --> 00:26:13,745
...regarding the accidental
damage to...

261
00:26:13,947 --> 00:26:16,609
There was nothing accidental about it.

262
00:26:18,551 --> 00:26:21,418
The department might have something
to say about that.

263
00:26:21,621 --> 00:26:24,089
Although the camera was destroyed...

264
00:26:24,290 --> 00:26:27,157
...I have the entire
incident on video.

265
00:26:28,695 --> 00:26:30,094
I see.

266
00:26:33,333 --> 00:26:34,493
And your proposal?

267
00:26:35,735 --> 00:26:39,364
We may be willing to drop
the lawsuit against the city...

268
00:26:39,572 --> 00:26:42,063
...but that depends
on Inspector Callahan.

269
00:26:44,043 --> 00:26:46,705
I'm sure the inspector
would be willing to...

270
00:26:46,913 --> 00:26:48,403
What do you have in mind?

271
00:26:50,984 --> 00:26:51,973
Dinner.

272
00:27:08,735 --> 00:27:11,101
I owe you an apology.

273
00:27:11,404 --> 00:27:13,838
You were right
about what I did the other day.

274
00:27:14,040 --> 00:27:17,532
I had no business intruding
on that girl's grief.

275
00:27:19,446 --> 00:27:21,004
I get too eager sometimes.

276
00:27:21,214 --> 00:27:24,308
In my rush to get the story,
I made an error in judgement.

277
00:27:24,517 --> 00:27:26,348
We all make those sometimes.

278
00:27:26,553 --> 00:27:29,021
No, I should have known better.

279
00:27:29,222 --> 00:27:30,780
I'm sorry.

280
00:27:31,891 --> 00:27:34,451
- Let me ask you, Miss Walker...
- Sam.

281
00:27:34,727 --> 00:27:35,819
Sam.

282
00:27:36,029 --> 00:27:37,053
Do you like cops?

283
00:27:38,131 --> 00:27:40,565
If they're not in my
rear-view mirror. Why?

284
00:27:42,335 --> 00:27:44,599
I wonder what
we're supposed to talk about...

285
00:27:44,804 --> 00:27:47,170
...other than the damaged camera.

286
00:27:47,373 --> 00:27:49,170
Oh, no, no, no.

287
00:27:49,375 --> 00:27:52,640
I'm letting the insurance company
deal with that.

288
00:27:53,780 --> 00:27:57,580
And I think I can be persuaded
to drop the lawsuit...

289
00:27:57,784 --> 00:27:59,684
...but I want something in return.

290
00:28:02,155 --> 00:28:03,247
What would that be?

291
00:28:03,590 --> 00:28:04,818
I want your story.

292
00:28:09,395 --> 00:28:10,225
What's that?

293
00:28:10,430 --> 00:28:12,864
I've done my homework on you.

294
00:28:13,066 --> 00:28:15,500
You've had quite a colorful career.

295
00:28:15,702 --> 00:28:17,397
Loot at this. You see...

296
00:28:17,604 --> 00:28:21,802
...there's a lot of interest right now
in the Janero case...

297
00:28:22,008 --> 00:28:23,873
...and the cop who put him in prison.

298
00:28:24,077 --> 00:28:28,446
Channel 8 is doing a news special
on organized crime in the Bay Area.

299
00:28:28,648 --> 00:28:32,778
But what I would like to do
is an in-depth profile...

300
00:28:32,986 --> 00:28:35,887
...of you, Inspector Harry Callahan.

301
00:28:36,089 --> 00:28:37,681
Sorry, I'm not interested.

302
00:28:37,891 --> 00:28:42,021
Why not? This latest attempt
on your life by one of Janero's men...

303
00:28:42,228 --> 00:28:45,129
You're not interested
in doing a story on me.

304
00:28:45,331 --> 00:28:47,299
You want blood. That's what sells...

305
00:28:47,500 --> 00:28:50,367
- Now wait a minute...
- No, you wait a minute.

306
00:28:50,570 --> 00:28:53,130
You people are interested
in death and mayhem...

307
00:28:53,339 --> 00:28:55,569
...and you don't care
how you get the story.

308
00:28:55,775 --> 00:29:00,109
That is not fair. That's not
the kind of journalism I do.

309
00:29:00,313 --> 00:29:02,941
To you I'm just a cop
with a price on his head.

310
00:29:03,149 --> 00:29:07,142
Let me tell you, I don't like
people saying they're gonna kill me.

311
00:29:07,353 --> 00:29:10,880
Nor do I like journalists using it
as a way to increase ratings.

312
00:29:11,090 --> 00:29:14,992
- What I was going to say...
- That's the end of the story.

313
00:29:31,210 --> 00:29:32,302
Sorry.

314
00:29:35,048 --> 00:29:37,346
The coroner's report last night...

315
00:29:37,850 --> 00:29:39,943
...said that Squares used speedballs.

316
00:29:40,153 --> 00:29:41,814
Injecting cocaine and heroin?

317
00:29:42,021 --> 00:29:43,545
But that's not what killed him.

318
00:29:43,756 --> 00:29:46,919
He was using an inhaler
with some new designer drug.

319
00:29:47,126 --> 00:29:49,219
A synthetic form of heroin.

320
00:29:49,429 --> 00:29:52,193
You mean something along the lines
of China White.

321
00:29:52,398 --> 00:29:55,196
Only a thousand times wore powerful.

322
00:29:55,401 --> 00:29:58,632
One snort and he went into
immediate respiratory failure.

323
00:29:58,838 --> 00:30:00,533
IKKnow what I'm trying to figure?

324
00:30:00,740 --> 00:30:02,401
Why is a guy like that...

325
00:30:02,609 --> 00:30:06,409
...screwing with synthetic junk
when he's got the real stuff?

326
00:30:06,613 --> 00:30:08,774
Maybe he didn't know
what he was using.

327
00:30:14,187 --> 00:30:15,347
Harry.

328
00:30:20,326 --> 00:30:21,156
Harry?

329
00:30:23,763 --> 00:30:25,424
Sorry about that.

330
00:30:28,735 --> 00:30:30,362
Get you next time.

331
00:30:36,909 --> 00:30:40,037
Check the cast and crew
for prior drug busts.

332
00:30:40,246 --> 00:30:45,013
I'll check with Narcotics to see if any
dealers are moving synthetic heroin.

333
00:30:45,318 --> 00:30:47,582
Harry, there's something here
you should see.

334
00:30:48,287 --> 00:30:51,256
<i>A story to be published</i>
<i>in today's</i> Tribune...

335
00:30:51,457 --> 00:30:55,587
<i>... reveals that director Peter Swan</i>
<i>and several other people involved...</i>

336
00:30:55,795 --> 00:31:00,664
<i>... in the film</i> Hotel Satan <i>were</i>
<i>playing a game called "The Dead Pool."</i>

337
00:31:00,867 --> 00:31:03,392
<i>According to sources,</i>
<i>the object of the game...</i>

338
00:31:03,603 --> 00:31:06,504
<i>... was for players to pick</i>
<i>eight Bay Area celebrities...</i>

339
00:31:06,706 --> 00:31:10,369
<i>... who might die</i>
<i>by a predetermined date.</i>

340
00:31:10,576 --> 00:31:15,377
<i>The winner was to possess the list</i>
<i>with the most dead celebrities.</i>

341
00:31:15,581 --> 00:31:17,708
<i>What makes this story significant...</i>

342
00:31:17,917 --> 00:31:22,911
<i>... is that rock star Johnny Squares</i>
<i>was on director Peter Swan's list.</i>

343
00:31:23,122 --> 00:31:25,920
<i>Although Swan would not comment...</i>

344
00:31:26,125 --> 00:31:29,458
<i>... we have confirmed that</i>
<i>there was such a game...</i>

345
00:31:29,662 --> 00:31:34,224
<i>... and Swan's production accountant,</i>
<i>Dean Madison, was also involved.</i>

346
00:31:34,467 --> 00:31:37,027
<i>Ironically, Madison was</i>
<i>killed yesterday...</i>

347
00:31:37,236 --> 00:31:40,728
<i>... in a tragic holdup attempt</i>
<i>that took place in Chinatown.</i>

348
00:31:43,810 --> 00:31:48,110
"There is no man who is master of the
breath of life so as to retain it...

349
00:31:48,314 --> 00:31:51,306
...and none has mastery
over the day of death.

350
00:31:51,517 --> 00:31:54,350
For the Lord of all
shows no partiality...

351
00:31:54,554 --> 00:31:56,112
...nor does He fear greatness...

352
00:31:56,322 --> 00:31:58,187
...because He himself
made the great...

353
00:31:58,391 --> 00:31:59,915
...as well as the small.

354
00:32:00,126 --> 00:32:02,924
And He provides for all alike.

355
00:32:03,696 --> 00:32:07,257
And the dust returns to the
earth, as it once was.

356
00:32:07,700 --> 00:32:11,295
And the life breath
returns to God, who gaveth."

357
00:32:18,678 --> 00:32:20,407
My condolences.

358
00:32:21,080 --> 00:32:23,640
Mrs. Dayton, I'm terribly sorry.

359
00:32:23,883 --> 00:32:26,875
Suzanne, I'm very sorry
for your trouble.

360
00:32:27,086 --> 00:32:28,383
Thank you.

361
00:32:30,189 --> 00:32:31,679
My sympathies, dear.

362
00:32:34,227 --> 00:32:37,856
Do you mind, gentlemen?
I happen to be at a funeral.

363
00:32:38,097 --> 00:32:40,031
I'd like to talk about your list.

364
00:32:40,233 --> 00:32:43,691
It's no big secret.
The cast and crew knew about it.

365
00:32:43,903 --> 00:32:47,100
The Dead Pool is just a harmless game.

366
00:32:47,306 --> 00:32:49,672
It sounds pretty sick to me.

367
00:32:50,243 --> 00:32:51,733
Let me tell you something.

368
00:32:52,111 --> 00:32:55,046
People are fascinated
with death and violence.

369
00:32:55,248 --> 00:32:57,148
That's why my films make money.

370
00:32:57,350 --> 00:33:00,649
They're an escape,
a vicarious release of fear.

371
00:33:00,853 --> 00:33:02,684
Same thing with this game.

372
00:33:02,889 --> 00:33:05,585
Nobody takes my films
or the Dead Pool seriously.

373
00:33:06,292 --> 00:33:09,819
Someone gave Squares the drugs
that killed him. Maybe you.

374
00:33:10,029 --> 00:33:13,487
You can't tie me to Johnny's death
because of a coincidence.

375
00:33:14,934 --> 00:33:19,200
My assistant and effects supervisor
played too. Why not talk to them?

376
00:33:19,405 --> 00:33:20,372
We will.

377
00:33:21,340 --> 00:33:23,433
But nobody on their list is dead yet.

378
00:33:23,643 --> 00:33:28,137
Johnny was a drug user and I predicted
he'd die this year. That's all.

379
00:33:28,347 --> 00:33:31,441
The idea is to pick celebrities
who won't make it...

380
00:33:31,651 --> 00:33:34,677
...because they're old, sick
or in a high-risk profession.

381
00:33:34,887 --> 00:33:36,377
Like police work?

382
00:33:36,856 --> 00:33:37,823
Nothing personal.

383
00:33:38,024 --> 00:33:40,584
I don't like being on your list, Swan.

384
00:33:40,793 --> 00:33:43,523
That's what this is really about,
isn't it?

385
00:33:43,729 --> 00:33:44,889
If you have a choice...

386
00:33:45,097 --> 00:33:47,793
Maybe I'll start my own Pool
and put you on it.

387
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:49,433
Are you threatening me?

388
00:33:50,069 --> 00:33:54,472
If you want to play the game,
you'd better know the rules, love.

389
00:34:13,259 --> 00:34:15,386
That's our report. I'm Patrick Snow.

390
00:34:15,595 --> 00:34:18,462
I'm Samantha Walker.
Thank you for being with us.

391
00:34:18,664 --> 00:34:20,632
Tune in tonight
for an exclusive report...

392
00:34:20,833 --> 00:34:23,233
...on chemical dependency
among celebrities.

393
00:34:23,436 --> 00:34:25,063
Who they are, why they do it...

394
00:34:25,271 --> 00:34:27,899
...and the price they pay.
Tonight at 11.

395
00:34:28,107 --> 00:34:29,404
Good night.

396
00:34:30,343 --> 00:34:31,970
And we're clear.

397
00:34:50,796 --> 00:34:53,060
Thought I'd seen the last of you.

398
00:34:53,266 --> 00:34:54,790
I saw your report yesterday.

399
00:34:55,001 --> 00:34:57,128
We confirmed it
with people in the game.

400
00:34:57,336 --> 00:35:02,103
Vicky Owens, Swan's assistant,
and effects supervisor, Jeff Howser.

401
00:35:02,441 --> 00:35:05,274
It didn't occur to you
to clear it with us first?

402
00:35:05,478 --> 00:35:07,036
I had to go with the story.

403
00:35:07,246 --> 00:35:10,773
The papers got the same tip.
I had to get the story out fast.

404
00:35:10,983 --> 00:35:13,178
Or someone else would get it first?

405
00:35:13,386 --> 00:35:15,616
- Something like that.
- How were you tipped?

406
00:35:15,821 --> 00:35:19,780
By mail. A copy of the Dead Pool
and a letter explaining it.

407
00:35:22,361 --> 00:35:24,693
- It's already started.
- What has?

408
00:35:24,897 --> 00:35:26,922
All the media bullshit.

409
00:35:27,166 --> 00:35:31,193
Newspapers print the Dead Pool
and it hurts our investigation.

410
00:35:31,404 --> 00:35:32,962
What bothers you...

411
00:35:33,172 --> 00:35:35,902
...is that we found out about
the Dead Pool first.

412
00:35:36,108 --> 00:35:40,477
You people take Janero and the Dead
Pool, add hype and distortion...

413
00:35:40,680 --> 00:35:42,307
...and innocent people get hurt.

414
00:35:42,515 --> 00:35:44,483
Aren't you overreacting?

415
00:35:44,684 --> 00:35:46,117
I've seen it happen.

416
00:35:46,319 --> 00:35:49,152
I don't like the hype, either...

417
00:35:49,355 --> 00:35:51,687
...but it happens when reporters
compete for a story.

418
00:35:52,058 --> 00:35:56,051
Why don't you start thinking about
your responsibility to the public?

419
00:35:57,563 --> 00:36:00,498
You can't kill the messenger
because of the message.

420
00:36:02,068 --> 00:36:06,402
I'm sorry, it wasn't my intention
to screw up your investigation.

421
00:36:07,306 --> 00:36:09,570
Here's the list. Now, excuse me.

422
00:36:12,111 --> 00:36:13,305
Thanks.

423
00:36:17,083 --> 00:36:18,607
It seems I owe you one.

424
00:36:21,620 --> 00:36:23,110
Dinner, that is.

425
00:36:26,292 --> 00:36:31,059
I was offered a job as an anchor
at this small, local station.

426
00:36:31,263 --> 00:36:32,696
Because...

427
00:36:32,965 --> 00:36:36,162
...I was first runner-up
in Miss Colorado.

428
00:36:36,369 --> 00:36:38,963
Colorado? We're right over here.

429
00:36:39,171 --> 00:36:43,574
But I had absolutely no experience,
just my bachelor's in journalism.

430
00:36:43,776 --> 00:36:47,644
But it was a way in, so I grabbed it.

431
00:36:50,783 --> 00:36:53,752
But I didn't just smile at
the camera and read copy.

432
00:36:53,953 --> 00:36:56,581
I did anything and everything
at this station.

433
00:36:56,789 --> 00:37:00,850
Sports, news, hard news, weather.

434
00:37:01,060 --> 00:37:02,994
I produced documentaries.

435
00:37:04,830 --> 00:37:06,764
I love San Francisco.

436
00:37:06,966 --> 00:37:08,593
But it isn't easy.

437
00:37:09,969 --> 00:37:12,130
Big city, big news.

438
00:37:13,039 --> 00:37:15,405
I had to prove myself all over again.

439
00:37:15,608 --> 00:37:17,269
Have you succeeded?

440
00:37:17,643 --> 00:37:18,871
Somewhat.

441
00:37:20,212 --> 00:37:21,645
Apparently not with you.

442
00:37:22,915 --> 00:37:27,284
I shouldn't complain. At least you
stayed for dinner this time.

443
00:37:29,088 --> 00:37:31,249
I'd still love to do your story.

444
00:37:31,824 --> 00:37:33,086
No, thanks.

445
00:37:33,359 --> 00:37:36,658
You're wrong about me, Callahan,
and what I want to do.

446
00:37:37,430 --> 00:37:39,364
I wish I could convince you.

447
00:37:39,799 --> 00:37:41,198
I'll tell you what.

448
00:37:41,801 --> 00:37:43,428
Let's think on it.

449
00:37:44,537 --> 00:37:45,435
Sounds fair.

450
00:37:48,174 --> 00:37:49,402
Thank you.

451
00:38:04,023 --> 00:38:07,288
It's the truth,
I don't care what you say.

452
00:38:14,266 --> 00:38:15,893
Hey, Callahan.

453
00:38:16,268 --> 00:38:18,828
- You're Callahan, aren't you?
- That's right.

454
00:38:19,038 --> 00:38:20,130
What can I do for you?

455
00:38:20,339 --> 00:38:22,739
You're the cop who put Janero away.

456
00:38:25,778 --> 00:38:28,338
All I want is your autograph.

457
00:38:30,116 --> 00:38:31,947
Can I shake your hand?

458
00:38:35,554 --> 00:38:37,021
I'd just like to thank you.

459
00:38:37,223 --> 00:38:40,522
It's about time somebody
did something about Janero.

460
00:38:40,726 --> 00:38:44,492
Could you sign it to
Chester Docksteder? That's me.

461
00:38:45,598 --> 00:38:46,997
Let me buy you a drink.

462
00:38:47,199 --> 00:38:48,666
Some other time.

463
00:38:49,268 --> 00:38:52,931
We need more cops like you.
That's what we need.

464
00:38:53,539 --> 00:38:55,700
I gotta change my shorts.

465
00:38:59,445 --> 00:39:01,174
What are you laughing at?

466
00:39:01,380 --> 00:39:04,110
This is your 15 minutes, Callahan.

467
00:39:04,650 --> 00:39:09,110
Andy Warhol said everybody's famous
for 15 minutes. Well, this is it.

468
00:39:09,321 --> 00:39:10,345
Swell.

469
00:39:26,205 --> 00:39:27,729
Was it your first autograph?

470
00:39:27,940 --> 00:39:29,100
Yeah.

471
00:39:29,375 --> 00:39:31,536
And I hope my last.

472
00:40:58,330 --> 00:41:00,059
You know something?

473
00:41:00,332 --> 00:41:03,267
I don't think Lou Janero
likes you very much.

474
00:41:15,180 --> 00:41:17,910
She's okay. Just a little shaken up.

475
00:41:24,089 --> 00:41:25,750
How're you doing, girl?

476
00:41:29,461 --> 00:41:33,227
Whatever they're paying you, Harry,
it couldn't be enough.

477
00:41:37,803 --> 00:41:39,327
My colleagues.

478
00:41:44,443 --> 00:41:46,343
I don't want to be the news.

479
00:41:48,013 --> 00:41:49,605
Let's get you out of here.

480
00:42:22,748 --> 00:42:24,716
You sure you want to see this guy?

481
00:42:24,917 --> 00:42:26,179
Yeah.

482
00:42:36,962 --> 00:42:38,259
Here's your animal.

483
00:42:38,797 --> 00:42:39,627
